== Results ==
[[File:Newspapers of Japan 20090831.jpg|thumb|Headlines of Japanese newspapers<br />(August 31, 2009)]]
[[File:45th House of Representatives of Japan seat composition.svg|thumb|Seating after the election.<br />{{colorbox|#FF8080}} [[Democratic Party of Japan|Democratic Party]] (308)<br />
{{colorbox|#00FFFF}} [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (119)<br />
{{colorbox|#FFFF00}} [[New Komeito Party|Komeito Party]] (21)<br />
{{colorbox|#000000}} [[Japanese Communist Party|Communist Party]] (9)<br />
{{colorbox|#FFB950}} [[Social Democratic Party (Japan)|Social Democratic Party]] (7)<br />
{{colorbox|#FF004C}} [[Your Party]] (5)<br />
{{colorbox|#3CE100}} [[People's New Party]] (3)<br />
{{colorbox|#D278FF}} [[Independent (politician)|Independents / Others]] (8)]]

The DPJ swept the LDP from power in a massive landslide, winning 308 seats (out of a total of 480 seats), while the LDP won only 119 seats<ref name="BBC"/> - the worst defeat for a sitting government in modern Japanese history.  This was in marked contrast to the [[Japanese general election, 1993|1993 election]], the only other time the LDP has lost an election.  In that election, the LDP remained by far the largest party in the House with well over 200 seats, despite losing its majority.  However, in the 2009 election the LDP was nearly 200 seats behind the DPJ. Of 83 [[Koizumi Children]] who became new LDP representatives in 2005, only 10 were reelected.

The DPJ won a strong majority in the House of Representatives, thus virtually assuring that Hatoyama would be the next prime minister.  Under the Constitution, if the House of Representatives and the House of Councilors cannot agree on a choice for prime minister, the choice of the House of Representatives is deemed to be that of the Diet.  Hatoyama was nominated as prime minister on September 16 and formally appointed later that day by [[Akihito|Emperor Akihito]].

However, the DPJ was just short of a majority in the House of Councillors, and fell just short of the 320 seats (a two-thirds majority) needed to override negative votes in the upper chamber.  Hatoyama was thus forced to form a coalition government with the [[Social Democratic Party (Japan)|Social Democratic Party]] and [[People's New Party]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/national/news/20090822p2a00m0na013000c.html |title=Hatoyama says DPJ will form coalition even if party performs well in election |date=2009-08-22 |publisher=Mainichi}}</ref>

